Project 4 -- Linear Regression¶

Part 1 - Getting Started¶

In this project, we are going to design a mathematical model that predicts electrical grid stability, as described in the paper below:

Schäfer, Benjamin, et al. 'Taming instabilities in power grid networks by decentralized control.' The European Physical Journal Special Topics 225.3 (2016): 569-582.

For this purpose, we are using the Electrical Grid Stability dataset which includes 10000 instances with 12 features describing the power grid's status. The goal is to unravel patterns and predict the stab column, which is a characteristic of the grid that represents its stability. Note that you can ignore the last column named stabf since this is a binary indicator showing whether the stability is above a certain threshold.

Here are the steps to complete this portion:

  1. Print the dataframe.
  2. Prepare your dataset as follows:
  • Using train_test_split from Sklearn, split the dataset into training and validation sets ($80\%$ training, $20\%$ validation). When splitting, set random_state=111.
  • Standardize the data manually according to the same method as StandardScaler from sklearn, but you may not directly use `StandardScaler'.
  • Insert a first column of all $1$s in both the training and validation data sets.
  1. Explain why we should not insert the column of $1$s prior to standardization.

The column of 1's is defined as a bias term and is not one of the features. Standardizing it would create unexpected values and affect the standardization of other features, so it should be added after standardization.

Part 2 - Linear Regression Using Direct Solution¶

Implement the direct solution of the linear regression problem on the training set.

Note: You should use scipy.linalg.inv to perform the inversion, as numpy.linalg.inv may cause an error.

Report the root-mean-square error (RMSE) for both the training and validation sets.

RMSE for training set: 0.0220

RMSE for validation set: 0.0218

You may use root_mean_squared_error from Sklearn for computing the RMSE.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import scipy

def rmse(yPred, y):
    return np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(yPred, y))

def Direct_sol(X_train, y_train, X_valid, y_valid):
    W = np.dot(scipy.linalg.inv(np.dot(X_train.T, X_train)), np.dot(X_train.T, y_train))

    y_pred_train = np.dot(X_train, W)
    y_pred_valid = np.dot(X_valid, W)
    RMSE_train = rmse(y_pred_train, y_train)
    RMSE_valid = rmse(y_pred_valid, y_valid)

    plt.scatter(X_train[:, 1], y_train, label='Data')
    plt.scatter(X_train[:, 1], y_pred_train, label='Prediction')
    print (f"RMSE on training set: {RMSE_train:.4f}")
    print (f"RMSE on validation set: {RMSE_valid:.4f}")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    return W, y_pred_train, y_pred_valid, RMSE_train, RMSE_valid

result = Direct_sol(X_train_1f, y_train, X_valid_1f, y_valid)

Part 3 - Full Batch Gradient Descent¶

We will now implement a "full batch" gradient descent algorithm and record the training time for our model. Recall that the full batch gradient descent is, $$w_t = w_{t-1} - \alpha~g_t$$ where $\alpha$ is the learning rate and $g_t$ is your gradient, computed on the entire data.

Here are the steps for this part:

  • Implement gradient descent for linear regression using a fixed learning rate of $\alpha= 0.01$, and iterate until your model's validation RMSE converges.

    We consider the gradient descent as having converged when RMSE on the validation set using gradient descent satisfies:

    $$ RMSE_\text{GD} \leq 1.0005 \times RMSE_\text{Direct Solution}$$

    where $RMSE_\text{Direct Solution}$ is the RMSE on the validation set using the direct solution that you calculated in the previous part.

    We refer to the quantity $RMSE_\text{Direct Solution}\times 1.0005$ as the convergence threshold (CT). Be sure to compute the gradients yourself! Take a look at the code provided in the tutorial.

  • Record the training time (from the first iteration until convergence) using the time.time() function.

  • Plot the training RMSE and the validation RMSE vs. epoch on the same figure.

  • Comment on overfitting/underfitting by observing the training and validation RMSE

    Hint: Initialize your weights with small random numbers (<$0.00001$) & please set np.random.seed(1001)

    The RMSE vs Epoch plot shows both training and validation RMSE decreasing smoothly, indicating a good fit to the dataset without significant overfitting or underfitting. The alignment of the two curves suggests that the model generalizes well for both existing and unseen data. With the validation RMSE converging at epoch 351, it demonstrates an efficient convergence with small initial weights and learning rate of 0.01. These parameters help the model to converge faster, revealing a significant parameter tuning and training process.

  • Explain the difference between epoch and iteration in the Gradient descent algorithm (SGD/mini-batch)?

    Eepoch is a complete loop of the entire training dataset, whereas iteration is a single update of the model parameters. The number of iterations in an epoch depends on the batch size. Smaller batch sizes result in more iterations per epoch because more batches are required to process the entire dataset. In gradient descent, each iteration processes a mini-batch, so it needs multiple iterations to complete one epoch.

import time

start_time = time.time() ## Records current time
np.random.seed(1001)

W, y_pred_train, y_pred_valid, RMSE_train, RMSE_valid = Direct_sol(X_train_1f, y_train, X_valid_1f, y_valid)

w = np.random.rand(X_train_1f.shape[1]).reshape(1, -1) * 1e-5 # initial weight
print(f"Initial weight: {w}")
lr = 0.01 # learning rate

# record rmse values
rmse_train_array = []
rmse_valid_array = []

for epoch in range(5000):
    y_train_pred = np.dot(X_train_1f, w.T).reshape(-1, 1)
    y_valid_pred = np.dot(X_valid_1f, w.T).reshape(-1, 1)

    curr_rmse_train = rmse(y_train_pred, y_train)
    curr_rmse_valid = rmse(y_valid_pred, y_valid)

    rmse_train_array.append(curr_rmse_train)
    rmse_valid_array.append(curr_rmse_valid)

    gradient = (1 / len(y_train_pred) * np.dot(X_train_1f.T, y_train_pred - y_train.to_numpy().reshape(-1, 1))).reshape(1, -1)
    w = w - lr * gradient

    if curr_rmse_valid <= RMSE_valid * 1.0005:
        print(f"Validation RMSE converges at epoch {epoch}")
        break

print(f"Final weights: {w}")

print("--- Total Training Time: %s (s) ---" % (time.time() - start_time))

# plot RMSE vs Epoch
plt.plot(rmse_train_array, label="Training RMSE")
plt.plot(rmse_valid_array, label="Validation RMSE")
plt.xlabel("Epoch")
plt.ylabel("RMSE")
plt.title("RMSE vs Epoch")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Write a function that performs mini-batch gradient descent until the convergence threshold (CT) is reached.

The inputs of that function are:

Your function will return the following arrays:

  • The final weights after training.
  • The training RMSE at each epoch.
  • The validation RMSE at each epoch.
  • An array that has the elapsed time from the start of the training process to the end of each epoch (e.g., if each epoch takes exactly 2 seconds, the array would look like: [2 4 6 8 ...]).

Notes:

  • use np.random.seed(1001) before setting the initial (random) weights

  np.random.seed(1001)

  ### YOUR CODE HERE ###

  • For certain batch sizes, GD might not converge to a solution. For that reason, you need to check the RMSE of the validation/training set at each epoch, and if it's getting larger and larger, you should stop the training for that case (the design is up to you!).

  • CT will help you to know when your model is converged.

  • Important: after each epoch, you need to shuffle the entire training set. This ensures that new mini-batches are selected for every epoch. Hint: use np.random.permutation.

Let's now use the function to investigate the effect of batch size on convergence. When the batch size is 1, we call that stochastic gradient descent. When the batch size equals the # of training data, it is full-batch (i.e., all data points are used at every iteration). Anywhere in between is mini-batch (we use some of the data).

  • Sweep different values for the mini-batch size (at least 5 values that converge), each time using a learning rate of $\alpha= 0.01$. Hint: Try batch sizes that are powers of two (e.g., 2,4,8,16,...). These batch sizes fit better on the hardware and may achieve higher performance.

Provide the following $3$ plots:

  1. Plot training and validation RMSE vs. epoch for all the converging batch sizes (some batch sizes might not converge) in a figure. The X-axis is Epoch # and the Y-axis is RMSE.
  2. Plot training and validation RMSE vs. time for all the converging batch sizes in a figure. The X-axis is Time, and the Y-axis is RMSE.
  3. Plot Total training time (y-axis) vs. Batch size (x-axis).

Describe your findings, including the main takeaways from each of your plots.

Plot 1: A smaller batch size causes more frequent updates and helps RMSE to reach the minimum faster across epochs. As shown on the plot, higher batch size, such as 512, starts with a large RMSE (approximately 0.036) and drops down to reach the convergence state using more number of epoch. However, it converges more smoothly as epoch increases. The validation RMSE trends are consistent with the training RMSE, indicating stable generalization across all batch sizes.

Plot 2: Similar to Plot 1, RMSE takes longer time to converge with larger batch sizes because they have a higher probability of missing local minima and perform fewer updates within a given time frame. Although smaller batch sizes are computationally intensive due to frequent updates, they are more time-efficient for tasks requiring rapid convergence.

Plot 3: The total training time decreases as the batch size increases initially, reaching its lowest point at batch size 16, which converges the fastest with the fewest epochs. However, for larger batch sizes like 256 and 512, the training time increases again due to the added computational load of processing more data per mini-batch.

In conclusion, I noticed that when batch size is small, RMSE converges faster with lower RMSE value, while larger batch size makes RMSE to converge in a longer time and larger number of epochs but the curves are smoother. Batch size equals to 16 leads to the best balance of training efficiency.

def mini_batch_gd(X_train, y_train, X_valid, y_valid, batch_size, lr, ct):
    start_time = time.time()
    np.random.seed(1001)

    # initial outputs
    w = np.random.rand(X_train.shape[1]).reshape(1, -1) * 1e-5 # initial weight
    rmse_train_array = []
    rmse_valid_array = []
    elapsed_times = []
    is_converged = False

    for epoch in range(5000):
        # shuffle entire training set, ensures new mini-batches are selected
        index = np.random.permutation(X_train.shape[0])
        X_train_shuffled = X_train[index]
        y_train_shuffled = y_train.to_numpy()[index].reshape(-1, 1)

        # apply mini-batches
        for i in range(0, X_train.shape[0], batch_size):
            X_batch = X_train_shuffled[i:i + batch_size]
            y_batch = y_train_shuffled[i:i + batch_size]

            y_batch_pred = np.dot(X_batch, w.T)
            gradient = (1 / len(y_batch)) * np.dot(X_batch.T, y_batch_pred - y_batch).reshape(1, -1)
            w = w - lr * gradient

        y_train_pred = np.dot(X_train, w.T).reshape(-1, 1)
        y_valid_pred = np.dot(X_valid, w.T).reshape(-1, 1)

        curr_rmse_train = rmse(y_train_pred, y_train)
        curr_rmse_valid = rmse(y_valid_pred, y_valid)

        rmse_train_array.append(curr_rmse_train)
        rmse_valid_array.append(curr_rmse_valid)

        elapsed_times.append(time.time() - start_time)

        if curr_rmse_valid <= ct:
            print(f"Validation RMSE converges at epoch {epoch}")
            is_converged = True
            break

        # stop training if validation/training RMSE get larger
        # is diverged if there are 5 continuous increases in RMSE
        count_valid_increase = 0
        count_train_increase = 0
        diverge = False
        for i in range(len(rmse_valid_array) - 1):
            if rmse_valid_array[i] < rmse_valid_array[i + 1]:
                count_valid_increase += 1
                if count_valid_increase >= 4:
                    print(f"Validation RMSE diverges at epoch {epoch}")
                    diverge = True
                    break
            else:
                count_valid_increase = 0

            if rmse_train_array[i] < rmse_train_array[i + 1]:
                count_train_increase += 1
                if count_train_increase >= 4:
                    print(f"Training RMSE diverges at epoch {epoch}")
                    diverge = True
                    break
            else:
                count_train_increase = 0

        if diverge:
            break

    return w, rmse_train_array, rmse_valid_array, elapsed_times, is_converged

Part 5 - Gradient Descent Learning Rate¶

Use the function that you designed in Part 4 to investigate the effect of learning rate on convergence.

  1. Pick 3 batch sizes that do not converge with a learning rate of $\alpha= 0.01$ (last part) and try to find a learning rate that results in convergence for each batch size. Report your findings in a table. Mention batch size, learning rate, and training and validation RMSE.

  2. Select the best batch size based on Part 4's fastest convergence time and sweep the learning rate (at least 10 values, all should converge) while applying Mini-batch GD.

  • Plot the training and validation RMSE vs. epoch (x-axis) for all the learning rates that you tried in a figure.
  • Plot the training and validation RMSE vs. time (x-axis) for all the learning rates that you tried in a figure.
  • Describe your findings, including the main takeaways from each of your plots.

In Plot 1, we can observe the RMSE of training and validation against the number of epochs for different learning rates ranging from 0.001 to 0.010. As epochs increases, RMSE consistently decreases across all learning rates, indicating model improvement. Also, higher learning rates such as 0.007, 0.008, and 0.009 achieve convergence more quickly compared to smaller learning rates like 0.001 and 0.002, which take longer to decrease.

Plot 2 illustrates RMSE vs. time, emphasizing the efficiency of training. Similar to Plot 1, larger learning rates lead to faster convergence, causing low RMSE in short time. This establishes that higher learning rates not only improve performance but also more time-efficient in this case. However, it may cause an overfitting with high learning rates.

As a result, higher learning rates for batch size 16 take shorter time and number of epochs to converge. But it has trade-offs. High learning rates may lead to overfitting because when the model converges too quickly, it may fail to predict on unseen data. It may miss the optimal solution as it overshoots during the training process. Also, this can lead to large updates to weights, making the model sensitive to noise in the training dataset instead of validation dataset.
